		<!-- message -->
		<div><br /> Ok Mik, here we go.<br />
<br />
It has been proven that standing natural mana regen naked is 1 mana per tick.<br />
<br />
I had 152 int= 1944 mana +100 in mana items so 2044 mana pool.<br />
<br />
First test I cast shock of fire (SOF) a 15 mana spell till oom. <br />
<br />
161 casts = 2415 mana<br />
Actual mana was 2044 +137 from regen (13 minutes 46 sec)= 2181<br />
Total gain = 234 mana or 234/2181 for 10.72% gain<br />
<br />
Second test was the exact same spells and setup but there seemed to be a some variance.<br />
<br />
166 Casts = 2490 mana<br />
Actual mana was 2044 +130 from regen (13 min 02 sec) = 2174<br />
Total gain = 316 mana or 316/2174 for 14.53% gain<br />
<br />
The third test I used big nukes then smaller ones so I cast less.<br />
<br />
4 SS at 450 mana<br />
2 draughts at 215 mana<br />
4 shocks at 15 mana<br />
total 2290 mana<br />
actual mana was 2044 (went quick)<br />
Total gain 246 mana or 246/2044 for 12.03% gain<br />
<br />
Those were with evocation and 200 Specialize. I am too fuzzy at the moment to draw any conclusions.<br />
<br />
-----------------------------------------------------<br />
Here is the test with abjuration (shields) with 50 spec<br />
<br />
I used a 25 mana shield. <br />
90 casts = 2250 mana<br />
actual mana was 2044 + 125 for regen or 2169<br />
Total gain of 81 mana or 81/2169 for 3.73%<br />
<br />
I used <br />
200 mana shield X 10 casts<br />
10 mana shield X 13 casts<br />
Total = 2130 mana<br />
actual mana was 2044 + 30 for regen or 2074<br />
total gain of 56 mana or 56/2074 for 2.7%<br />
<br />
Obviously the 200 spec does better but was too hard to get definitive numbers conclusions. will re look at this later.<br />
<br />
Night gang<br />
<br />
Fasty<br />
<br />
<br />
-----just gonna throw up a hypothesis. 50 spec is a 3% gain/ 200 is a 12% gain on average. Seems to fit those numbers. I would say offhand that with the SCM2 you have that you picked up a 6-7% gain. Not bad. Took Fury 3 levels to get that much gain. Will be interesting to see SCM3 numbers. <br /></div>
